Date: 0/0/1869
Source: TrNZI
Author:
Vol / Page: 1/III/31
Edition:
Quote: Besides which the following roots and plants were often eaten, viz., the roots (cooked) of the Panahi (<i>Calystegia sepium</i>); of the Maikaika (<i>Arthropodium cirrhatum</i>); ... the roots of the little sugary Ti-koraha (<i>Cordyline stricta</i>), of the large Ti, or `Cabbage Tree' (<i>C. australis</i>), and of the large Fern, Para, (<i>Marattia salicina</i>).
Notes: (Colenso Botany North Isd)

Date: 1/7/2006
Source: Dominion Post Indulgence
Author:
Vol / Page: 19
Edition:
Quote: Panahi is the well-behaved cousin in the convolvulus family .. Calystegia soldanella, or panahi .. knows its rightful place and like all plants in their rightful place, doesn't become weedy. Panahi is a perennial herb that occupies the edges of coasts and lakes and helps to stabilise sand.
